        html: '<p>Captain N\'s Videoland was a narrative device that allowed DiC to licence characters from across multiple game publishers — Capcom\'s Mega Man, Konami\'s Simon Belmont, Nintendo\'s own characters — under a single creative umbrella. This was commercially complex but creatively liberating: writers could construct stories that no individual game franchise would have permitted. A crossover between Mega Man and Simon Belmont, battling Mother Brain while guided by a human teenager from real-world Northridge, California, was the kind of narrative that existed only because the show\'s format required it. The result was genuinely strange television: a product that reflected the breadth of the NES library in a way nothing else did.</p><p>The creative liberties taken with individual characters reflected the production pace and the minimal publisher oversight of the period. Capcom\'s Mega Man was redesigned so completely that his creator Keiji Inafune reportedly expressed dismay at the result. Simon Belmont was characterised as a vain, cowardly braggart entirely unlike the stoic monster hunter of the games. Kid Icarus spoke in a verbal tic that added "-icus" to the end of words. These characterisations were inventions of DiC\'s writing staff working from minimal character briefs and with no systematic creative oversight from the original game developers.</p>',
